I've had businesses in NY & NC. Besides the government fees to having different businesses licenses there was no reason to pay someone to do it for me. I've had a few businesses and currently restarting a new venture altogether. While I'm waiting on an LLC, I got a DBA in the meantime. It at least allows me to do business while things fall in line. I talk with business attorneys, CPA's and accountants regularly so I know the best move and the next move.

It depends on the business. Not a straight forward answer. But you can do a "DBA" (doing business as) with your local government. You can do an LLC, S-Corp, Ect.... with your state government. Each has there own pros and cons. Do you know exactly what you want to do?

If you want to register your business in Europe, you could look at Estonia's e-residency program which would make you a digital citizen of that country and they'll send you a passport which you can use to sign all your documents from abroad. I don't know much about experience based products. But I think you may be right about the growing demand for them. I think most of it, like the samurai one, can be viewed as tourism. But some of them, like "experience being famous" don't seem like they may do good, but it can still be regarded as a profitable tourist idea. 

A random example of an experience based service: a service which allows you to live an olden day life for a day or two (I mean, without electricity, phones and stuff. In the middle of a village, with just nothing but ancient utensils... gramophone etc) might be worth trying. I don't know if there are any services like that. But things like this will be a lot of fun. And creating a market out of it could benefit the society and draw in open minded people.

P.S. I think it might be fine to allow phones, inside an "ancient village". Because there are too many people who cannot live without it.

That's actually correct. At one point we cannot avoid exploiting the dopamine pathways. Because it is fundamental to how we humans function. 

Yes I agree, providing people with a platform to organize, share and discover is the right way to go. If you look at services like <http://stackexchange.com|stackexchange.com> (and a few subreddits that are good), even if you get addicted to them, you will always end up gaining from them: by forcing yourself to learn, or by genuinely helping others in exchange for more points (which translates to corporate or academic social reputation).

I wouldn't say that my main focus is on maslow's hierarcy, i think it's just a neat little idea which backs-up my hunch that there's a growing  (and largely unmet) demand for experience based products. My guess is that demand for these sorts of commodities(?) will grow much more as economies become more service-based, and manufacturing/primary industry goes full robot.

On your other point about the dopamine aspect,  i've often been held back by this thought; that willful engagement of people into almost any kind of business model is akin to selling likes on facebook, ie the dopamine cycle is always a fundamental force that's being exploited at some level. However i'm not sure there's any way to escape that particular circuit until humans are able to leave their bodies. until then, i think growth, expansion and moderated addictions should be encouraged and profited from. i guess the key question is, as usual; what kind of growth, and to what end? I agree that the celebrity for a day thing is like selling canned narcisism -  without getting too philosophical, there's definitely more ethical ways to provide people an uplifting experience. You could even avoid the whole dilemma and simply provide a platform for people to efficiently organize / share/ discover their own methods?

Fulfilling each level to move forward, does not always have to be induced externally. Satisfaction begins within ones own view of this world. There is a chance that making someone famous for 2 hrs could become addictive (I could be wrong). External means do not always help. 

Social networks make use of this unrest within people to make money. Giving people a dopamine boost, through likes, comments and shares, never cause them to stop doing what they keep doing: spending time on social media. Instead it just keeps increasing. Giving people a dopamine boost for money is exactly like selling "social media likes" to users. Again, this is just my view and I could be wrong. 

I think the only way someone can satisfy the hierarchy is by wanting to be satisfied with what they have. By the way, the Japanese Samurai thing was awesome! I really want to try that some day!

Please correct me if I'm wrong, I think your main focus is on Maslow's hierarchy. That's an awesome idea! Exposing people to fame, for example, will make them understand how famous people have their own challenges. Or simply being exposed to such a situation will make them get used to it, not wanting it anymore and thus fulfilling one of the levels in the hierarchy. This must help them move one level up, in the hierarchy. More like how a child will be very excited about his new flying helicopter (toy), and later get used to playing with it (causing it to remain under a bundle of toys, forgotten, forever).

Hi Steve Fisher! I think I understand. This site, <http://famousforaday.co|famousforaday.co>, honestly I many never have come up with something like this myself! but really I think you could go beyond this kind of temporary pop-level stuff and do something more meaningful?

attachments.text: Tokyo - First you'll change the clothes into "kimono" and "hakama" is samurai style. Introducing with tea ceremony Matcha green tea and Wagashi sweets Next we'll watch a real Japanese katana—a traditional sword used by the samurai of ancient and feudal Japan. Then you'll learn how to handle it with unsharpened katana. We'll also do a traditional Zen <http://meditation.It|meditation.It> called "Rituzen". After doing meditation, you will be calm mind and you can cut one bundle of straw with real sword. Through using with real katana yourself, you can feel one part of swordsmanship as samurai. Lastly, you'll watch a performance using real katana by host. We'll discuss what we've seen and learned over tea. This experience has no flashy production and luxury, but you can feel the "real". You can enjoy not only training but also total samurai culture with this time. More than over 20country, 900 people joined in a year. From families, couples to martial artists, various people touched and enjoyed the “real” samurai world! If you bring a camera, you can taking some pictures of samurai pauses which learning in this experience! If there are no dates availablilty on the calendar, please message me:)
